3-(carboxymethyl)−1-methyl-1 H-imidazol-3-ium bromide (ILIM). 90 % yield, 1HNMR (400 MHz, DMSO‑d6
) δ (in ppm) = 3.9 (s, 3H; NCH3), 5.2 (s, 2H), 7.7 (t, 2H), 9.2 (s, 2H), 12.2 (s, OH). 13CNMR (100 MHz, DMSO‑d6
) δ (in ppm) = 36.4, 50.1, 123.6, 124.1, 138.0, 168.5.

3-(carboxymethyl)−1-methyl-1 H-benzo[d]imidazole-3-ium bromide (ILBIM). 90 % yield, 1HNMR (400 MHz, DMSO- d6
) δ (in ppm) = 4.1 (s, 3H; NCH3), 5.5 (s, 2H), 7.7 (t, 2H), 8.0 (t, 2H), 9.7 (s, 1H). 13CNMR (100 MHz, DMSO- d6
) δ (in ppm) = 33.9, 47.9, 114,1, 127.2, 131.8, 144.0, 168.4.

To elucidate the antibacterial behavior of synthesized CDs-NH2, ILBIM@CDs and ILIM@CDs in reference to antibacterial drug Ridinilazole, molecular docking studies have been conducted. For E. coli bacteria docking studies have been conducted against DNA Gyrase receptor (Organism: E. coli K-12), and the docking studies demonstrate a typical direction for compounds to bind (CDs-NH2, ILBIM@CDs and ILIM@CDs) in the catalytic binding pocket of DNA gyrase receptor (PDBID: 6YD9). Hereby, we described the binding aspects of synthesized (CDs-NH2, ILBIM@CDs and ILIM@CDs) and compare with the standard ligand (Ridinilazole) which was docked against DNA Gyrase protein. CDs-NH2, ILBIM@CDs and ILIM@CDs; bind in the catalytic domain of the DNA Gyrase receptor. ILBIM@CDs binding interaction (Hydrogen Bonding) with a backbone of DNA Gyrase receptor with Glu86, simultaneously ILIM@CDs having hydrogen bond interaction with Asp46, Asp73, and Arg136. CDs-NH2, ILBIM@CDs and ILIM@CDs superimposition with standard drug (Ridinilazole) ligand revealed the identical interaction as that seen in the catalytic domain of DNA Gyrase receptor (as shown in Fig. 8
                        , Table 4
                        ). Additionally, enhanced antibacterial activity of ILBIM@CDs and ILIM@CDs against standard drug; Ridinilazole, were found as compared to CDs-NH2 (−2.825); based on docking score i.e., −6.598, −6.577 and −3.865 respectively.
